  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "The following Sunday, we traveled about three miles to attend services, with everyone riding on horseback. The men carried their rifles, Buck included, holding them between their legs or leaning them conveniently against the walls. The Shepherdsons followed the same practice. The sermon was quite tedious, focusing on themes like brotherly love and similar tiresome topics; however, everyone praised it as an excellent message. They discussed it at length on the journey home, debating faith, good deeds, divine grace, and predestination with such intensity that it felt like one of the most exhausting Sundays I had ever experienced.\n\nRoughly an hour after our midday meal, everyone was drowsing, either in their seats or their bedrooms, and the atmosphere grew quite stagnant. Buck and a dog lay sprawled on the lawn, fast asleep in the sunlight. I headed toward our room, intending to catch a nap myself. I discovered the lovely Miss Sophia standing in her doorway, which was adjacent to ours. She ushered me inside, closed the door quietly, and inquired if I liked her. I confirmed that I did. She then asked if I would perform a favor for her in secret, and I agreed. She explained that she had left her Testament in the church pew between two other volumes and requested that I sneak out, retrieve it, and keep the matter to myself. I promised to do so. I crept out and made my way up the road. The church was empty, save for a couple of hogs, as the building had no locks and the animals enjoyed the cool wooden floor during the summer heat. You might notice that most people only attend church when necessary, but hogs are different.\n\nI pondered to myself that something was afoot; it seemed unnatural for a young woman to be so anxious over a Bible. I shook the book, and a small slip of paper fell out with the words “Half-past two” scribbled in pencil. I searched the rest of the volume but found nothing else. Unable to decipher the meaning, I tucked the paper back inside. Upon returning home and heading upstairs, I found Miss Sophia waiting at her door. She pulled me inside and locked it. She checked the Testament until she located the note, and upon reading it, her expression brightened. Before I could react, she hugged me tightly, called me the best boy in the world, and reminded me to tell no one. Her face flushed for a moment, and her eyes sparkled, making her look remarkably beautiful. I was quite surprised, but once I recovered, I asked what the note meant. She inquired if I had read it, and when I said no, she asked if I could read handwriting. I told her I could only read large print. She then claimed the paper was merely a bookmark to save her place, and told me I could go off and play."
}

