  "rewritten_text": "He continued rambling on, clearly enjoying the sound of his own voice, and frequently brought up his funeral orgies again, until the duke could no longer tolerate it. He scribbled “obsequies, you old fool” on a small piece of paper, folded it, and began making gestures to pass it over the heads of the crowd to him. The king read the note, tucked it away, and remarked: “Poor William, despite his affliction, his heart is always in the right place. He wants me to invite everyone to the funeral—he wants me to ensure they all feel welcome. He needn’t have worried, though; that was exactly my intention.” He then proceeded to wander along, entirely composed, and continued inserting his funeral orgies into his speech just as he had before. When he did it for the third time, he explained: “I use the word orgies, not because it is the standard term—for obsequies is the common one—but because orgies is the accurate term. Obsequies is no longer used in England; it has fallen out of fashion. We say orgies in England now. Orgies is superior because it defines the concept more precisely. It is a word derived from the Greek orgo, meaning outside, open, or abroad, and the Hebrew jeesum, meaning to plant or cover up; hence, inter. So, you see, funeral orgies is an open or public funeral.” He was the most insufferable person I had ever encountered. Suddenly, the iron-jawed man laughed directly at him. Everyone was appalled. They all exclaimed, “Why, doctor!” and Abner Shackleford added: “Why, Robinson, haven’t you heard? This is Harvey Wilks.” The king smiled enthusiastically, extended his hand, and said: “Is it my poor brother’s dear friend and physician? I—” “Keep your hands off me!” the doctor interrupted. “You talk like an Englishman, do you? It is the most pathetic imitation I have ever heard. You, Peter Wilks’s brother! You are a fraud, that is what you are!” The crowd reacted with great distress. They gathered around the doctor, attempting to calm him and explain how Harvey had demonstrated in countless ways that he was indeed Harvey, knowing everyone by name, even the names of the dogs, and they begged him not to wound Harvey’s feelings or the poor girls’ feelings. It was futile; he continued to rage, insisting that any man claiming to be an Englishman who could not mimic the dialect better than that was a liar and a fraud. The poor girls clung to the king, weeping, when suddenly the doctor turned on them. He declared: “I was your father’s friend, and I am yours; I warn you as a friend, an honest one who wishes to protect you from harm and trouble, to turn your backs on that scoundrel and have nothing to do with him, that ignorant tramp with his absurd Greek and Hebrew. He is a transparent impostor who arrived here with a collection of empty names and facts he gathered somewhere, which you mistake for evidence, aided by these foolish friends who should know better.”"
}

