model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "TWAIN_HUCKLEBERRY_FINN_023",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "I once reasoned that it would be far better for Jim to remain a slave back home with his family, provided he had to be a slave at all, and I considered writing to Tom Sawyer to have him inform Miss Watson of Jim’s location. I quickly abandoned that idea for two reasons: she would be furious and repulsed by his perceived treachery and lack of gratitude for running away, leading her to sell him down the river immediately. Even if she didn't, people naturally look down on an ungrateful slave, and they would make Jim suffer for it, leaving him feeling degraded and ashamed. Furthermore, consider my own position! It would become common knowledge that Huck Finn assisted a slave in escaping, and if I ever encountered anyone from that town again, I would be so humiliated I would be ready to grovel at their feet. That is how it goes: a person commits a shameful act and then wishes to avoid the repercussions. They believe that as long as the deed remains secret, it carries no disgrace. That was precisely my situation. The more I pondered this, the more my conscience tormented me, and the more wicked and base I felt. Finally, when it struck me that this was clearly the hand of Providence striking me, signaling that my sins were being observed from heaven while I was stealing a poor woman’s slave who had never harmed me, and that there is a Higher Power watching who will not permit such wretched behavior to continue indefinitely, I was so terrified I nearly collapsed. I attempted to justify my actions by claiming I had been raised to be wicked and therefore was not entirely at fault, but an inner voice countered, “You had the opportunity to attend Sunday school; had you gone, you would have been taught that those who behave as you have regarding that slave are destined for eternal fire.”\n\nIt caused me to tremble. I nearly resolved to pray, hoping to cease being the boy I was and become a better person. I knelt down, yet the words failed to materialize. Why? It was futile to attempt to conceal the truth from Him, or from myself. I understood perfectly why the words would not come. My heart was not in the right place; I was not being honest; I was acting hypocritically. I pretended to renounce my sins, yet deep within, I clung to the greatest one of all. I tried to force my lips to declare that I would do the right thing and write to the slave’s owner to disclose his whereabouts, but in my heart, I knew it was a falsehood, and He knew it as well. You cannot offer a prayer that is a lie—I discovered that for myself."
}

