model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "TWAIN_HUCKLEBERRY_FINN_023",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "I once told myself it would be a thousand times better for Jim to be a slave back home with his family, since he had to be a slave anyway, and that I should write to Tom Sawyer and have him tell Miss Watson where Jim was. But I quickly abandoned that idea for two reasons: she would be furious and disgusted at his dishonesty and ingratitude for running away, and she would immediately sell him down the river again. Even if she didn't, everyone naturally looks down on an ungrateful Black man, and they would make Jim feel it constantly, leaving him feeling degraded and ashamed. And then, think of me! It would get around that Huck Finn helped a Black man gain his freedom; if I ever saw anyone from that town again, I would be so ashamed I would want to crawl on the ground. That is how it goes: a person does something shameful, and then they do not want to face the consequences. They think as long as they can hide it, it is not a disgrace. That was exactly my situation. The more I thought about it, the more my conscience gnawed at me, and the more wicked and low I felt. Finally, when it suddenly struck me that this was the clear hand of Providence slapping me in the face, letting me know my wickedness was being watched from heaven while I was stealing a poor woman’s property—someone who had never harmed me—and that there is a God who is always watching and will not allow such miserable behavior to go beyond a certain point, I nearly collapsed from fear. I tried my best to justify it by saying I was raised to be wicked and was not entirely to blame, but something inside kept saying, “You could have gone to Sunday school; if you had, they would have taught you that people who act the way you have been acting regarding that man go to eternal fire.”\n\nIt made me shiver. I almost decided to pray and see if I could stop being the kind of boy I was and become better. So, I knelt down. But the words would not come. Why wouldn't they? It was no use trying to hide it from Him, or from myself. I knew very well why they would not come. It was because my heart was not right; it was because I was not being honest; it was because I was being two-faced. I was pretending to give up sin, but deep inside I was holding onto the biggest one of all. I was trying to make my mouth say I would do the right thing and go write to that man’s owner to tell her where he was, but deep down I knew it was a lie, and He knew it too. You cannot pray a lie—I found that out."
}

