model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "TWAIN_HUCKLEBERRY_FINN_030",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "As she departed, she gazed into my eyes with a gaze both constant and kind, remarking: “The door shall remain unlocked, Tom, and the window and the pole are accessible; yet you will behave, won’t you? You will not leave? Do it for my sake.” Heaven knows I desired to depart to check on Tom and fully intended to do so, but following that request, I would not have left for all the kingdoms on earth. Still, she and Tom occupied my thoughts, causing me to sleep fitfully. Twice during the night, I descended the pole and crept toward the front, observing her seated by her candle in the window, her gaze fixed upon the road and tears in her eyes. I longed to assist her, yet could do nothing but vow never to cause her further sorrow. Upon waking at dawn for a third time, I slid down to find her still there; her candle had nearly burned out, and her aged gray head rested upon her hand as she slumbered. CHAPTER XLII. The old man returned from town before breakfast, having found no trace of Tom. Both sat at the table in silence, looking somber, their coffee cooling as they neglected their meal. Eventually, the old man inquired: “Did I hand you the letter?” “What letter?” “The one I retrieved from the post office yesterday.” “No, you did not give me any letter.” “I must have forgotten it.” He searched his pockets, then retrieved it from where he had set it down and presented it to her. She remarked: “Why, it is from St. Petersburg—it is from Sis.” I thought a walk might benefit me, but I remained motionless. Before she could open the envelope, she dropped it and ran, having spotted something. I saw it too. It was Tom Sawyer on a mattress, accompanied by the old doctor, and Jim, wearing her calico dress with his hands bound behind him, followed by a crowd. I concealed the letter behind the nearest object and hurried forward. She threw herself toward Tom, weeping, and cried: “Oh, he is dead, he is dead, I know he is dead!” Tom turned his head slightly and mumbled something, indicating he was not in his right mind. She raised her hands and exclaimed: “He is alive, thank God! That is enough!” She kissed him quickly and rushed toward the house to prepare the bed, issuing rapid commands to the servants and everyone else as she moved. I trailed the men to see how they would handle Jim, while the doctor and Uncle Silas followed Tom inside. The men were quite irritable, and some suggested hanging Jim as a warning to other enslaved people, hoping to prevent them from attempting to escape like Jim had, which caused such immense trouble and kept the family in a state of terror for days."
}

