model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "TWAIN_TOM_SAWYER_002",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Admittedly, the knife was incapable of slicing anything, yet it was a genuine Barlow, and that fact held unimaginable magnificence—though why the boys of the West ever believed such a tool could be imitated to its detriment is a profound puzzle that will likely stay that way. Tom managed to scratch the cupboard with it and was preparing to work on the bureau when he was summoned to get ready for Sunday school. Mary handed him a tin bowl of water and a bar of soap, and he stepped outside to place the basin on a small bench; he then dipped the soap into the water, set it aside, rolled up his sleeves, poured the water onto the ground with care, and walked into the kitchen to scrub his face vigorously with the towel hanging behind the door. However, Mary took the towel away and remarked, \"Aren't you ashamed, Tom? You shouldn't be so naughty. Water won't cause you any harm.\" Tom felt slightly rattled. The basin was filled again, and this time he hovered over it for a moment, summoning his courage; he took a deep breath and started. When he walked into the kitchen a moment later, eyes squeezed shut and hands feeling for the towel, his face was dripping with the respectable evidence of soap and water. Yet, upon stepping out from the towel, he still was not quite clean, as the scrubbed area ended abruptly at his chin and jawline like a mask; beneath that border lay a dark region of unwashed skin that extended down his chest and around the back of his neck. Mary took charge, and once she finished, he was a fellow human being, uniform in complexion, with his damp hair carefully combed and the short ringlets styled into a delicate, balanced look. [He secretly flattened the curls with great effort, plastering his hair against his scalp, as he considered curls to be womanly, and his own were a constant source of misery.] Mary then produced a set of clothes that had served only for Sundays over the past two years—they were simply known as his \"other clothes,\" which gives us an idea of the extent of his wardrobe. The girl tidied him up once he had finished dressing; she fastened his tidy jacket to his chin, folded his large shirt collar over his shoulders, brushed him off, and topped him with his speckled straw hat. He appeared significantly better but felt quite uneasy. He was just as uncomfortable as he appeared, for the restriction of tidy, whole clothing irritated him. He prayed that Mary would overlook his shoes, but his wish was crushed; she covered them completely with tallow, as was the tradition, and presented them. He grew angry and complained that he was constantly forced to do things he disliked. But Mary said, in a coaxing tone, \"Please, Tom—be a good boy.\" So he put on the shoes while grumbling. Mary was soon prepared, and the three children departed for Sunday school—a location Tom despised with all his might, though Sid and Mary enjoyed it. Sunday school lasted from nine until ten-thirty, followed by the church service."
}

