Henry, requesting some reading material and recalling their appointment for eight-fifteen that evening. “Await a reply,” he instructed, passing it to him, “and usher the men inside.” Within moments, another knock followed, and Mr. Hubbard, the renowned frame-maker from South Audley Street, entered accompanied by a somewhat unrefined young helper. Mr. Hubbard was a florid, red-whiskered man of small stature, whose appreciation for fine art was significantly moderated by the chronic poverty of the artists who patronized him. Generally, he never departed his shop. He expected clients to visit him. Yet he consistently made an exception for Dorian Gray. There was a quality about Dorian that captivated everyone. Merely seeing him was a delight. “How may I assist you, Mr. Gray?” he inquired, massaging his plump, spotted hands. “I decided to do myself the honor of visiting personally. I have just acquired a magnificent frame, sir. I secured it at an auction.”"
