  "rewritten_text": "Slowly, pale fingers of light slide through the drapes, appearing to quiver. Mute, dark shadows take on strange, jagged forms as they creep into the room’s corners to huddle. Beyond the walls, birds rustle in the foliage, laborers begin their daily tasks, and the wind sighs and sobs as it descends from the hills, circling the quiet house as if hesitant to disturb those sleeping, yet compelled to summon slumber from its violet depths. Layer after layer of thin, dark mist is drawn away, and gradually, objects regain their shapes and hues, allowing us to observe the dawn recreating the world in its ancient design. The pale mirrors recover their reflected existence. The extinguished candles remain where they were placed, accompanied by the partially read volume we were examining, the artificial flower worn at the dance, or the letter we dreaded opening or had perused too frequently. Everything appears unchanged. From the illusory shadows of night, the familiar reality of our lives returns. We are forced to take it up exactly where we paused, and a crushing awareness of the need to persist in the same monotonous cycle of habitual actions creeps over us, or perhaps a desperate wish that our eyes might wake to a world refashioned in the dark for our delight—a world where objects possess new forms and colors, hold different secrets, and where the past has no place or survives without the burden of duty or remorse, since even the memory of joy carries bitterness and the recollection of pleasure brings pain.\n\nDorian Gray believed that the creation of such worlds was the primary purpose, or among the primary purposes, of existence. In his pursuit of sensations that were simultaneously novel and pleasurable, while holding that quality of strangeness vital to romance, he frequently embraced ways of thinking he knew were foreign to his character. He would surrender to their delicate influence, and once he had absorbed their essence and sated his mental curiosity, he would abandon them with a detached indifference that is not at odds with a truly passionate nature, and which, according to some contemporary psychologists, is often a prerequisite for it.\n\nIt was once whispered that he intended to convert to Roman Catholicism, and the Roman liturgy certainly held a profound fascination for him. The daily sacrifice, more solemn than any from the ancient world, moved him as much by its magnificent denial of sensory evidence as by the elemental simplicity of its components and the enduring sorrow of the human drama it aimed to represent. He enjoyed kneeling upon the chilly marble floor to observe the priest, clad in a stiff, embroidered dalmatic, moving the tabernacle veil aside with slow, white hands, or elevating the ornate, lantern-like monstrance containing the pale wafer that one might wish to believe is truly the “panis cælestis,” the bread of angels, or, dressed in the vestments of Christ’s Passion, breaking the Host into the chalice while striking his breast in penance for his sins."
}

