model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_DORIAN_GRAY_019",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "It was marvelous even to peruse accounts of the opulence belonging to those long deceased. He then shifted his focus to needlework and the tapestries that served as wall paintings within the cold chambers of northern European lands. As he delved into this topic—possessing a remarkable talent for becoming entirely consumed by whatever task he undertook—he felt a sense of melancholy regarding the decay that time inflicts upon exquisite and miraculous objects. He, however, had avoided such a fate. Seasons turned, yellow daffodils blossomed and withered repeatedly, and nights of terror recounted their tale of disgrace, yet he remained unaltered. No winter season scarred his features or dulled his youthful, petal-like complexion. How contrasting this was to physical items! Where had they vanished? What became of the magnificent saffron-hued garment, depicting the gods battling giants, crafted by dark-skinned maidens to delight Athena? Where was the massive velarium Nero had spanned over the Roman Colosseum, that colossal purple sail portraying the starry heavens and Apollo steering a chariot pulled by white horses with golden reins? He yearned to behold the peculiar napkins fashioned for the Priest of the Sun, which displayed every delicacy and dish required for a banquet; the burial shroud of King Chilperic, adorned with three hundred golden bees; the eccentric garments that provoked the Bishop of Pontus, featuring “lions, panthers, bears, dogs, forests, rocks, hunters—everything, in truth, that an artist might replicate from the natural world”; and the tunic once donned by Charles of Orleans, upon whose sleeves were stitched the lyrics of a song starting “Madame, je suis tout joyeux,” with the musical notation rendered in gold thread, each square-shaped note of that era composed of four pearls. He studied the chamber prepared at the Rheims palace for Queen Joan of Burgundy, embellished with “one thousand three hundred and twenty-one parrots, created in needlework and emblazoned with the royal crest, alongside five hundred and sixty-one butterflies, their wings similarly decorated with the queen’s arms, all executed in gold.” Catherine de Medicis possessed a mourning bed of black velvet dusted with crescents and suns. Its hangings were of damask, featuring foliage wreaths and garlands set against a gold and silver backdrop, bordered with pearl embroidery, situated in a room draped with the queen’s emblems in cut black velvet upon silver cloth. Louis XIV displayed gold-stitched caryatids fifteen feet in height within his quarters. The royal bed of Sobieski, King of Poland, consisted of Smyrna gold brocade stitched with turquoises and verses from the Koran. Its frame was of chased silver gilt, lavishly inlaid with enameled and jeweled medallions. It had been seized from the Turkish encampment outside Vienna, and the banner of Mohammed had once rested beneath its shimmering gilt canopy.\n\nConsequently, throughout an entire year, he endeavored to gather the most refined examples of textile and needlework he could discover, acquiring delicate Delhi muslins, intricately decorated with gold-thread palmettes and studded with iridescent beetle wings; Dacca gauzes, known in the Orient for their transparency as “woven air,” “running water,” and “evening dew”; exotic patterned fabrics from Java; complex yellow Chinese wall hangings; volumes bound in tan satins or pale blue silks and adorned with fleurs-de-lis, birds, and figures; veils of lacis crafted in Hungarian point; Sicilian brocades and rigid Spanish velvets; Georgian pieces featuring gold coins; and Japanese Foukousas, with their greenish golds and brilliantly feathered birds."
}

