  "rewritten_text": "‘Conversely,’ he added, ‘should he truly refuse to employ the Rising Sun Lubricator, we must remove his chains. It would be entirely unfeasible to rest with such a racket occurring just beyond the sleeping quarters.’\n\nThroughout the remainder of the week, they remained unbothered, the sole matter drawing notice being the persistent reappearance of the blood-mark upon the library floor. This was indeed quite peculiar, given that Mr. Otis consistently locked the door each evening and kept the windows firmly secured. Furthermore, the shifting, chameleon-like hue of the mark prompted significant discussion. On certain mornings it appeared a muted, almost Indian red, then shifted to vermilion, then a deep purple, and on one occasion, as they gathered for family devotions following the modest customs of the Free American Reformed Episcopalian Church, they discovered it to be a vivid emerald-green. These kaleidoscopic shifts naturally provided the group with much amusement, and wagers regarding the matter were readily placed each night. The solitary individual who failed to appreciate the humor was young Virginia, who, for reasons unknown, was consistently quite troubled by the sight of the stain, nearly weeping the morning it turned emerald-green.\n\nThe ghost manifested a second time on Sunday evening. Shortly after retiring, they were abruptly startled by a tremendous clatter in the hallway. Hurrying down, they discovered that a substantial suit of antique armor had slipped from its pedestal and collapsed onto the stone floor, while the Canterville ghost sat in a high-backed chair, massaging his knees with a look of intense pain. The twins, having armed themselves with pea-shooters, immediately fired two pellets at him with the precision only achieved through extensive and diligent practice on a writing-master, while the American Minister leveled his revolver at him, demanding he raise his hands in accordance with Californian custom. The spirit sprang up with a fierce cry of indignation and drifted through them like vapor, snuffing out Washington Otis’s candle as he moved, thereby plunging them into complete darkness. Upon gaining the landing, he regained his composure and resolved to unleash his famous, hellish laughter. He had found this tactic remarkably effective on numerous occasions. It was rumored to have turned Lord Raker’s hair white overnight and had certainly caused three of Lady Canterville’s French governesses to resign before their first month concluded. He proceeded to emit his most terrifying laugh, until the ancient vaulted ceiling echoed repeatedly, yet no sooner had the chilling sound faded than a door swung open, and Mrs. Otis emerged wearing a light blue dressing-gown. ‘I fear you are quite unwell,’ she remarked, ‘and I have fetched you a bottle of Dr. Dobell’s tincture. Should your trouble be indigestion, you will find it a superb cure.’ The ghost stared at her with rage and immediately began readying himself to transform into a massive black dog, a feat for which he was rightfully famous, and to which the family physician always credited the lasting insanity of Lord Canterville’s uncle, the Hon. Thomas Horton."
