sed and leaving them all in total darkness. Upon reaching the top of the staircase, he recovered himself and decided to let out his celebrated peal of demonic laughter. He had found this extremely useful on more than one occasion. It was said to have turned Lord Raker’s wig gray in a single night and had certainly caused three of Lady Canterville’s French governesses to quit before their month was up. He accordingly laughed his most horrible laugh until the old vaulted roof rang again and again, but hardly had the fearful echo died away when a door opened and Mrs. Otis came out in a light blue dressing gown. “I am afraid you are not feeling well,” she said, “and I have brought you a bottle of Dr. Dobell’s tincture. If it is indigestion, you will find it a most excellent remedy.” The ghost glared at her in fury and immediately began preparing to turn himself into a large black dog, a feat for which he was justly famous and to which the family doctor always attributed the permanent idiocy of Lord Canterville’s uncle, the Honorable Thomas Horton."
