  "rewritten_text": "CHAPTER IV\n\nBy the following day, the specter felt exhausted and frail. The intense strain of the previous month had taken its toll, leaving his nerves frayed and causing him to jump at the smallest sound. He remained in his quarters for five days before deciding to abandon the matter of the library’s bloodstain. If the Otis household had no desire for it, they surely did not merit it. They were clearly individuals of a base, physical nature, entirely unable to grasp the deeper meaning of sensory manifestations. The subject of ghostly appearances and the manifestation of astral forms was, naturally, a separate issue beyond his influence. He felt a grave responsibility to haunt the hallway weekly and to moan from the expansive bay window on the first and third Wednesday of every month, and he could not see a way to shirk these duties with integrity. While his past life had been wicked, he remained remarkably diligent regarding his supernatural obligations. Consequently, for the following three Saturdays, he patrolled the hall between midnight and three in the morning, exercising extreme care to remain unseen and unheard. He took off his footwear, stepped gingerly across the ancient, decaying floorboards, donned a heavy black velvet mantle, and made sure to apply the Rising Sun Lubricator to his chains. I must admit that he felt quite reluctant to utilize this final measure of maintenance. Nevertheless, one evening while the family dined, he crept into Mr. Otis’s room and stole the container. Though initially embarrassed, he later realized the product had its merits and assisted his endeavors to some extent. Regardless, he was not left in peace. Cords were frequently placed across the passage, causing him to stumble in the gloom, and once, while attired as ‘Black Isaac, the Huntsman of Hogley Woods,’ he suffered a painful tumble after stepping on a butter-slide the twins had fashioned from the Tapestry Chamber doorway to the top of the wooden stairs. This final indignity infuriated him, prompting him to plan one last attempt to reclaim his status and authority; he decided to confront the rude young students the following evening as his famous ‘Reckless Rupert, or the Headless Earl.’\n\nHe had not donned this costume for over seven decades—not since he had terrified the lovely Lady Barbara Modish so thoroughly that she abruptly ended her betrothal to the current Lord Canterville’s grandfather and eloped to Gretna Green with the dashing Jack Castleton, insisting that nothing could persuade her to join a family that permitted such a ghastly spirit to roam the terrace at dusk. Poor Jack was later killed in a duel by Lord Canterville on Wandsworth Common, and Lady Barbara passed away from a broken heart at Tunbridge Wells before the year concluded, so, by all accounts, it had been a resounding triumph."
}

