rance of the Tapestry Chamber to the top of the oak staircase. This final insult enraged him so much that he decided to make one last effort to assert his dignity and social standing. He resolved to visit the rude young boys the following night in his famous persona of ‘Reckless Rupert, or the Headless Earl.’\n\nHe had not used this disguise for over seventy years. In fact, he had not worn it since he frightened the beautiful Lady Barbara Modish so badly that she broke off her engagement to the current Lord Canterville’s grandfather. She ran away to Gretna Green with the handsome Jack Castleton, declaring that nothing would convince her to marry into a family that allowed such a horrible ghost to walk the terrace at twilight. Poor Jack was later killed in a duel by Lord Canterville on Wandsworth Common, and Lady Barbara died of a broken heart at Tunbridge Wells before the year ended, so, in every way, the haunting had been a great success."
}

model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_LORD_ARTHUR_STORIES_015",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "“I am terribly sorry, Mr. Otis,” the boy panted, “but I cannot bring myself to eat while Virginia remains missing. Please, do not be cross with me; had you permitted our engagement last year, this entire ordeal would have been avoided. You will not send me away, will you? I cannot leave! I refuse to go!”\n\nThe Minister found himself smiling at the attractive young rogue, feeling moved by his loyalty to Virginia. Leaning down from his mount, he patted the boy’s shoulders gently and replied, “Very well, Cecil, if you insist on staying, I suppose you must accompany me, though I shall need to find you a hat in Ascot.”\n\n“Oh, forget about my hat! I only want Virginia!” the young Duke exclaimed with a laugh, and they rode quickly toward the train station. There, Mr. Otis asked the station-master if anyone matching Virginia’s description had been spotted on the platform, but he received no information. The station-master did, however, send telegrams along the line and promised that a careful watch would be maintained. After purchasing a hat for the young Duke from a draper who was closing his shop, Mr. Otis rode toward Bexley, a village four miles distant, which was known as a gypsy gathering spot due to the adjacent common. They woke the local constable but learned nothing from him, and after searching the entire common, they turned back, arriving at the Chase around eleven o’clock, exhausted and nearly devastated. Washington and the twins were waiting at the gate-house with lanterns, as the driveway was pitch black. No sign of Virginia had been found. The gypsies had been located in Brockley meadows, but she was not among them; they explained their abrupt departure by claiming they had miscalculated the date of Chorton Fair and left in haste to avoid being late. They were, in fact, quite upset to learn of Virginia’s disappearance, as they felt indebted to Mr. Otis for letting them camp on his grounds, and four of them had remained to assist in the search. The carp-pond had been searched, and the entire Chase had been scoured, all to no avail. It was clear that, for the night at least, Virginia was gone; it was with heavy hearts that Mr. Otis and the boys walked to the house, followed by the groom with the horses and pony. Inside the hall, they encountered a cluster of terrified servants, and in the library, Mrs. Otis lay on a sofa, nearly hysterical with fear, while the housekeeper bathed her brow with eau-de-cologne. Mr. Otis immediately insisted she eat and ordered supper for everyone. It was a somber meal, with almost no conversation; even the twins were subdued and solemn, as they loved their sister dearly. Once they finished, Mr. Otis ignored the young Duke’s pleas and sent everyone to bed, stating that nothing more could be accomplished until morning, when he would wire Scotland Yard to request that detectives be dispatched at once."
}

