model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_LORD_ARTHUR_STORIES_016",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "They were truly grand, particularly a ruby necklace featuring an antique Venetian mount, which stood as a magnificent example of sixteenth-century craftsmanship. Their worth was so immense that Mr. Otis felt significant hesitation regarding his daughter’s acceptance of them.\n\n‘My lord,’ he remarked, ‘I am aware that in this nation, the concept of mortmain applies to jewelry just as it does to real estate. It is evident to me that these pieces are, or ought to be, family heirlooms. I must therefore insist that you return them to London, viewing them as assets restored to you under peculiar circumstances. As for my daughter, she is but a child and, fortunately, possesses little interest in such symbols of idle extravagance. Furthermore, Mrs. Otis—who is quite an authority on art, having spent several winters in Boston during her youth—has informed me that these gems hold substantial monetary value and would command a high price if sold. Given these facts, Lord Canterville, I trust you see why I cannot permit them to stay with my family. Such vain trinkets, while perhaps fitting for the British nobility, are entirely inappropriate for those raised on the austere and, I believe, enduring principles of republican simplicity. I should add that Virginia hopes you might allow her to keep the box as a keepsake of your unfortunate and misguided ancestor. Since it is quite aged and somewhat damaged, you might see fit to grant her wish. Personally, I am surprised that my child would express sympathy for medievalism in any form, though I suppose it stems from the fact that Virginia was born in a London suburb shortly after Mrs. Otis returned from a visit to Athens.’\n\nLord Canterville heard the Minister’s address with great seriousness, tugging at his grey moustache occasionally to conceal a suppressed smile. Once Mr. Otis finished, he shook his hand warmly and replied, ‘My dear sir, your delightful daughter performed a vital service for my ill-fated ancestor, Sir Simon, and my family and I owe her a great debt for her remarkable bravery. The jewels are rightfully hers, and, by heaven, I suspect that if I were cruel enough to reclaim them, the old rogue would rise from his grave within a fortnight to make my life miserable. Regarding their status as heirlooms, nothing qualifies as such unless specified in a will or legal deed, and these jewels were previously unknown. I assure you I have no more claim to them than your butler does, and I imagine that when Miss Virginia matures, she will enjoy wearing such lovely items. Moreover, you overlook the fact, Mr. Otis, that you purchased the furniture and the ghost at a valuation. Anything belonging to the spirit became your property immediately, for regardless of Sir Simon’s nocturnal activities in the hallway, he was legally deceased, and you acquired his belongings through that transaction.’"
}

