ened very seriously to the Minister’s speech, tugging at his grey moustache occasionally to hide an involuntary smile. When Mr. Otis finished, he shook his hand cordially and said, ‘My dear sir, your charming daughter performed a very important service for my unlucky ancestor, Sir Simon, and my family and I are greatly indebted to her for her marvelous courage and grit. The jewels are clearly hers, and, honestly, I believe that if I were heartless enough to take them from her, the wicked old fellow would be out of his grave within a fortnight, making my life a living hell. As for them being heirlooms, nothing is an heirloom unless it is specified in a will or legal document, and the existence of these jewels was entirely unknown. I assure you I have no more claim to them than your butler does, and when Miss Virginia grows up, I expect she will be pleased to have pretty things to wear. Besides, you forget, Mr. Otis, that you purchased the furniture and the ghost at a valuation, and anything that belonged to the ghost passed immediately into your possession. Regardless of any activity Sir Simon may have shown in the corridor at night, legally speaking, he was dead, and you acquired his property through your purchase.’"
}

