  "rewritten_text": "They were truly magnificent, especially a ruby necklace in an old Venetian setting, which was a superb example of sixteenth-century craftsmanship. Their value was so high that Mr. Otis felt uneasy about letting his daughter keep them.\n\n“My lord,” he said, “I know that in this country, the laws of inheritance often apply to jewelry just as they do to land. It is clear to me that these jewels are, or should be, family heirlooms. I must ask you to take them back to London and consider them a part of your property that has been returned to you under unusual circumstances. As for my daughter, she is just a child and, I am happy to say, has little interest in such symbols of idle luxury. My wife, Mrs. Otis—who is quite an expert on art, having spent several winters in Boston as a girl—has informed me that these gems are very valuable and would sell for a high price. Given this, Lord Canterville, I am sure you understand why I cannot allow my family to keep them. Such vain trinkets, while perhaps suitable for the British aristocracy, are entirely out of place for those raised on the strict, enduring principles of republican simplicity. I should mention that Virginia would like to keep the box as a memento of your unfortunate ancestor. Since it is very old and in poor condition, you might be willing to grant her request. Personally, I am surprised that my daughter would express sympathy for anything medieval, though I suppose it is because she was born in a London suburb shortly after her mother returned from a trip to Athens.”\n\nLord Canterville listened to the Minister’s speech with a serious expression, occasionally tugging at his gray mustache to hide a smile. When Mr. Otis finished, he shook his hand warmly and said, “My dear sir, your charming daughter did my unlucky ancestor, Sir Simon, a great service. My family and I are deeply indebted to her for her incredible courage. The jewels are rightfully hers. Honestly, if I were heartless enough to take them from her, I believe the old fellow would rise from his grave within two weeks and make my life miserable. As for them being heirlooms, nothing is an heirloom unless it is specified in a will or legal document, and no one even knew these jewels existed. I assure you, I have no more claim to them than your butler does. When Miss Virginia grows up, I am sure she will be happy to have such pretty things to wear. Besides, you forget, Mr. Otis, that you purchased the furniture and the ghost as part of the estate. Anything that belonged to the ghost became your property the moment you bought the house. Regardless of how active Sir Simon was in the hallway at night, he was legally dead, and you acquired his belongings through your purchase.”"
}

