model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_LORD_ARTHUR_STORIES_022",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Poetry and the theater were his two primary sources of joy. During his time at Eton, he constantly engaged in costumed performances of Shakespeare, and upon arriving at Trinity, he joined the A.D.C. during his initial term. I recall feeling quite envious of his theatrical talents. I was foolishly attached to him, likely because we were such opposites. I was a clumsy, frail boy with oversized feet and a face covered in freckles. Freckles are as common in Scottish lineages as gout is among the English. Cyril often remarked that he would choose the gout over the freckles; he placed an exaggerated importance on physical beauty, even presenting a lecture to our debate club arguing that being attractive was superior to being virtuous. He was undeniably striking. Those who disliked him—Philistines, university instructors, and divinity students—often dismissed him as merely pretty, but his features held far more depth than that. I consider him the most magnificent person I have ever encountered, possessing unmatched grace in his gestures and a captivating demeanor. He enchanted everyone worth enchanting, along with many who were not. He was frequently headstrong and irritable, and I often perceived him as deeply dishonest, though I believe this stemmed mostly from his excessive need to be liked. Poor Cyril! I once remarked that he settled for trivial victories, but he simply chuckled. He was dreadfully pampered. I suspect all delightful individuals are pampered; it is the core of their allure.\n\n‘Regardless, I must recount Cyril’s acting. You are aware that women were not permitted to perform with the A.D.C., at least not during my era. I am uncertain of the current rules. Naturally, Cyril was always assigned the female roles, and when they staged As You Like It, he portrayed Rosalind. It was a stunning portrayal. In truth, Cyril Graham remains the only flawless Rosalind I have witnessed. It is impossible to convey the elegance, subtlety, and sophistication of his work. It caused quite a stir, and the cramped little theater was packed every evening. Even now, reading the play brings Cyril to mind. It seemed as if it were composed specifically for him. The following term, he graduated and moved to London to study for a diplomatic career. However, he never applied himself. He passed his days studying Shakespeare’s Sonnets and his nights at the theater. Naturally, he was desperate to pursue acting. It took all the effort Lord Crediton and I could muster to stop him. Perhaps he would still be with us had he followed that path. Offering advice is always foolish, but offering sound advice is entirely disastrous. I trust you will never commit that mistake. If you do, you will surely regret it.\n\n‘Now, to reach the heart of the matter, I received a note from Cyril one day, requesting that I visit his chambers that night."
}

