model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_LORD_ARTHUR_STORIES_022",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "The two things that truly brought him joy were poetry and acting. At Eton, he was constantly dressing up and reciting Shakespeare, and when we started at Trinity, he joined the A.D.C. during his first term. I recall being quite jealous of his acting. I was foolishly devoted to him, likely because we were so different in certain ways. I was a rather awkward, frail boy with enormous feet and a face covered in freckles. Freckles are common in Scottish families just as gout is in English ones. Cyril used to say he preferred the gout of the two, but he always placed an absurdly high value on physical appearance, even reading a paper to our debating society to argue that it was better to be attractive than to be virtuous. He was certainly remarkably handsome. People who disliked him—Philistines, college tutors, and young men studying for the clergy—would claim he was merely pretty, but there was much more to his face than simple prettiness. I believe he was the most magnificent person I ever encountered, and nothing could surpass the grace of his movements or the charm of his manner. He fascinated everyone worth fascinating, along with many who were not. He was often willful and petulant, and I used to think him terribly insincere. I believe this was mainly due to his excessive desire to please. Poor Cyril! I once told him he was satisfied with very cheap triumphs, but he only laughed. He was dreadfully spoiled. I suspect all charming people are spoiled; it is the secret of their appeal.\n\nHowever, I must tell you about Cyril’s acting. You know that no actresses were permitted to perform at the A.D.C., at least not during my time. I am not sure how it is now. Naturally, Cyril was always cast in the female roles, and when *As You Like It* was produced, he played Rosalind. It was a marvelous performance. In fact, Cyril Graham was the only perfect Rosalind I have ever seen. It would be impossible to describe the beauty, delicacy, and refinement of his portrayal. It caused a massive sensation, and the cramped little theater, as it was then, was packed every night. Even now, when I read the play, I cannot help but think of Cyril. It might have been written for him. The following term, he earned his degree and moved to London to study for the diplomatic service. But he never did any work. He spent his days reading Shakespeare’s Sonnets and his evenings at the theater. He was, of course, desperate to go on the stage. It was all that I and Lord Crediton could do to stop him. Perhaps if he had become an actor, he would be alive today. It is always foolish to give advice, but giving good advice is absolutely fatal. I hope you never fall into that error. If you do, you will regret it.\n\nWell, to get to the real point of the story, one day I received a letter from Cyril asking me to come over to his rooms that evening."
}

