model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "WILDE_LORD_ARTHUR_STORIES_023",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "To him, as to me, they were poems of serious and tragic significance, wrung from the bitterness of Shakespeare’s heart and sweetened by the honey of his lips. He was even less willing to admit that they were merely a philosophical allegory, or that in them Shakespeare was addressing his Ideal Self, Ideal Manhood, the Spirit of Beauty, Reason, the Divine Logos, or the Catholic Church. He felt, as I believe we all must, that the Sonnets are addressed to an individual—a specific young man whose personality for some reason seems to have filled Shakespeare’s soul with both terrible joy and terrible despair.\n\nHaving cleared the way, Cyril asked me to set aside any preconceived notions I might have formed on the subject and to give his own theory a fair and unbiased hearing. The problem, he pointed out, was this: Who was that young man of Shakespeare’s day who, without being of noble birth or even noble character, was addressed in terms of such passionate adoration that we can only wonder at the strange worship and feel almost afraid to unlock the mystery of the poet’s heart? Who was he whose physical beauty became the very cornerstone of Shakespeare’s art, the source of his inspiration, and the incarnation of his dreams? To view him simply as the object of certain love poems is to miss their entire meaning; for the art Shakespeare discusses in the Sonnets is not the art of the Sonnets themselves—which were to him merely slight, private things—but the art of the dramatist to which he is always alluding. The person to whom Shakespeare said, 'Thou art all my art, and dost advance / As high as learning my rude ignorance,' and to whom he promised immortality, 'Where breath most breathes, even in the mouths of men,' was surely none other than the boy-actor for whom he created Viola, Imogen, Juliet, Rosalind, Portia, Desdemona, and Cleopatra herself. This was Cyril Graham’s theory, developed, as you can see, purely from the Sonnets themselves. Its acceptance depended not so much on demonstrable proof or formal evidence, but on a kind of spiritual and artistic intuition, by which alone he claimed the true meaning of the poems could be discerned. I remember him reading that fine sonnet—'How can my Muse want subject to invent, / While thou dost breathe, that pour’st into my verse / Thine own sweet argument, too excellent / For every vulgar paper to rehearse? / O, give thyself the thanks, if aught in me / Worthy perusal stand against thy sight; / For who’s so dumb that cannot write to thee, / When thou thyself dost give invention light? / Be thou the tenth Muse, ten times more in worth / Than those old nine which rhymers invocate; / And he that calls on thee, let him bring forth / Eternal numbers to outlive long date'—and pointing out how completely it corroborated his theory. Indeed, he went through all the Sonnets carefully, showing, or imagining he showed, that according to his new explanation, things that had seemed obscure, evil, or exaggerated became clear, rational, and of high artistic significance, illustrating Shakespeare’s concept of the true relationship between the art of the actor and the art of the dramatist."
}

